Objective :¶

To apply knowledge and skills of Python programming and business analytics to organize and analyze real-life data for meaningful insights.

Executive summary :¶

Crowdfunding means collecting funds for a project or commercial endeavor by soliciting contributions from a large number of people using an online platform. Our project focuses on Kiva.org, one of the world's most popular crowdfunding platforms.

Kiva.org is a prosocial crowdfunding platform where people from all around the world lend money to people in need. Kiva's purpose is to alleviate poverty in underdeveloped nations by allowing crowd-funded interest-free loans to underprivileged individuals and organizations. Kiva has made $1.63 billion in loans to over 4 million borrowers in 77 countries from over 1.9 million lenders since its inception in 2005. Despite its rapid expansion, Kiva has managed to keep a 96.2 percent repayment rate.

In our project, we are going to predict the status of the loan either 'funded' or 'notfunded' based on different variables(features). We have use two models "Logistic Regression" and "Decision Tree" for data modeling.

Project motivation/background :¶

Kiva.org, which was founded in 2005, is one of the largest online crowdfunding platforms in the world, allowing people to lend money to under represented entrepreneurs all around the world. Kiva's objective is to "connect people through loans to alleviate poverty," and it aims to give safe and cheap access to capital in areas where traditional banking services are unavailable, allowing people to become entrepreneurs and create possibilities for themselves and their families.

Kiva serves borrowers and lenders via the internet. Lenders who are willing to invest look through the various profiles of people looking for microcredit based on the loan request and borrower's attributes and invests on them. Kiva does not get any income on the loans it facilitates, and neither do Kiva lenders. Borrowers, on the other hand, pay interest to the financing process's intermediates, known as field partners, who are effectively the ones that carry the majority of the risk.

Kiva is active in 77 underdeveloped countries and collaborates with 304 field partners, according to statistics obtained in March 2015. In comparison to many other lending systems, Kiva stands out for its work with field partners. The field partners' purpose is to help the process along by creating a local presence and advancing funds to the borrowers prior to posting the loan request on the Kiva platform, allowing the borrowers to get a head start on their business.Kiva has made $1.63 billion in loans from over 1.9 million lenders since its inception in 2005. Kiva has managed to keep a 96.2 percent repayment rate. Considering different criteria, Kiva will decide whether to fund the loan to the borrower.

Data description :¶

Our data used in this project is obtained from Kiva site. The snapshots of Kiva data are provided in their site https://www.kiva.org/build/data-snapshots. We're working with the data in the csv file.Three data tables: loans.csv, lenders.csv, and loans_lenders.csv that maps which lender gives to which project are provided. The target variable used for the prediction is STATUS which is a nominal data type also called as the dependent variable.The input variables are the ones which plays prominent role in determining the status of the loan.

loans_lenders Data :
Variable names and descriptions of lender and loan characteristics:
LOAN_ID - identification number of the loan.This is unique for each loan.
LENDERS - list of lenders for a particular loan

Loans Data :
Variable names and descriptions of loan characteristics:
LOAN_ID - identification number of the loan.This is unique for each loan.
LOAN_NAME - name of the person taking loan
ORIGINAL_LANGUAGE - language of the borrower
DESCRIPTION - reason of taking the loan
DESCRIPTION_TRANSLATED - translated version of the description
FUNDED_AMOUNT - The amount of the loan already funded.
LOAN_AMOUNT - the loan amount requested.
STATUS - status of the loan
IMAGE_ID - id of image
VIDEO_ID - id of video
ACTIVITY_NAME - activity for which loan is taken
SECTOR_NAME - sector for which loan is taken
LOAN_USE - reason for which loan is used
COUNTRY_CODE - code of the borrower country
COUNTRY_NAME - name of the borrower country
TOWN_NAME - town of the borrower
CURRENCY_POLICY - currency policy representing shared or standard
CURRENCY_EXCHANGE_COVERAGE_RATE - conversion rate of the currency
CURRENCY - name of the currency
PARTNER_ID - field partner id
POSTED_TIME - loan request posted time
PLANNED_EXPIRATION_TIME - loan expiration time
DISBURSE_TIME - loan pay out time
RAISED_TIME - Time at which the loan amount is allocated
LENDER_TERM - repaying time of loan to the lender
NUM_LENDERS_TOTAL - total number of lenders for one loan id
NUM_JOURNAL_ENTRIES - document number of financial transactions
NUM_BULK_ENTRIES - bulk entry number
TAGS - tags used to identify the loan request reason
BORROWER_NAMES - names of the borrowers
BORROWER_GENDERS - gender of the borrowers
BORROWER_PICTURED - true/false values
REPAYMENT_INTERVAL - Period of time granted for repayment, in months.Repayment interval as irregular/monthly/bullet
DISTRIBUTION_MODEL - loan distribution model

Lenders data :
Variable names and descriptions of lender characteristics:
PERMANENT_NAME - permanent name/unique name of the lender
DISPLAY_NAME - display name of the lender
MAIN_PIC_ID - image id of the lender
CITY - city of the lender
STATE - state of the lender
COUNTRY_CODE - country code of the lender
MEMBER_SINCE - member since id
PERSONAL_URL - personal webpage of the lender
OCCUPATION - occupation of the lender
LOAN_BECAUSE - reason for lending loan
OTHER_INFO - other information given by lender
LOAN_PURCHASE_NUM - The number which describes the purchase of the loan
INVITED_BY-The invited by represents the referred person details
NUM_INVITED- the num_invited represented as 0 or 1.Number of lenders that responded to a particular loan request.

Our purpose is to build a model that predicts whether a loan can get funded based on loan features. 1) Deleting the records with the category we can ignore.
2) Recoding the three categories to two categories (funded, notfunded)
The recoded variable will be our target variable.

Our goal is to create a model that can anticipate the funding process based on the facts found in the data, which includes loan traits and attributes. We'll look at the data and try to extract the funding details, as well as find the attributes in the dataset that can help us come to the conclusion that the loan has been funded, and the remaining unneeded attributes can be removed from the dataset so that the dataset only contains the required attributes.

At this stage, our major goal is to remove any undesirable observations from the loans dataset, such as duplicates or irrelevant ones. During data collection, duplicate observations are the most common. Duplicate data can be created by combining records from multiple locations, collecting data, or receiving data from consumers or multiple lending departments and categories. Because our present data is acquired by Kiva rather than by us, it is preferable to assess the data collection and delete any unneeded data. The removal of redundant or unnecessary data from our collection will be our primary goal immediately. When we see something that isn't relevant to the current problem we're trying to solve, we call it an irrelevant observation. From the loans file, missing data can range from missing sequences, incomplete features, missing files, inadequate information, data input errors, and so on.

We will now delete all records with the status 'fundraising' from our database because they are no longer relevant to our next steps. Because we want to make the modifications to our dataset permanently, we'll use the drop command to ignore the fundraising data by setting it to True. We'll acquire the dataset that doesn't have fundraising status in our loans dataset when we finish the first stage.

We will replace the records of "expired," "refunded," and "notfunded" with "notfunded" because both records transmit the same record facts. We will also change the record name to a common one so that we can analyze the data more thoroughly.

Examining the variable 'LOAN_AMOUNT'.
1) Checking the distribution. What is the value of outliers if we use 3*IQR to define?
2) Removing the outliers.
3) Creating a new variable by taking log of this variable.

The interquartile range concept will be utilized now, for analyzing the distribution and the dispersion of data, we will use the IQR concept and will split the data as required with respect to quartiles. The observations which fall outside the mentioned quartiles are removed. We will remove the outliers by dropping the data which is above the upper range and below the lower range. The log function is utilized for creating a new variable by taking the log of the LOAN AMOUNT.

In [9]:
#describe the 'LOAN_AMOUNT' to check the distribution
loansdf['LOAN_AMOUNT'].describe()
Q3=np.quantile(loansdf['LOAN_AMOUNT'] , 0.75)
Q1=np.quantile(loansdf['LOAN_AMOUNT'] , 0.25)

#IQR 
IQR = (Q3 - Q1)
print(IQR)

lowerVal = (Q1 - (3 * IQR))
upperVal = (Q3 + (3 * IQR))

#remove the outliers
loansdf.drop(loansdf[ (loansdf['LOAN_AMOUNT'] > upperVal) | (loansdf['LOAN_AMOUNT'] < lowerVal) ].index ,
             inplace=True)
#taking log and creating new variable
loansdf['LOAN_AMOUNT_LOG']=np.log(loansdf['LOAN_AMOUNT'])
loansdf['LOAN_AMOUNT_LOG'].value_counts()

Finding the difference between 'POSTED_TIME' and 'DISBURSE_TIME'. Creating a new variable 'PREDISBURSE' if the 'DISBURSE_TIME' is before 'POSTED_TIME'.

'POSTED_TIME' and 'DISBURSE_TIME' are the variables which describes the posted time details and disburse time details with respect to datetime function of panda. The 'PREDISBURSE' variable is created with respect to 'POSTED_TIME' and 'DISBURSE_TIME'. The 'PREDISBURSE' variable has the values where the 'DISBURSE_TIME' values less than 'POSTED_TIME' values.

Examining variable 'CURRENCY_EXCHANGE_COVERAGE_RATE'. Checking the unique values for this variable and the missing value count?
Before we rush to replace missing values with mode, we ask the question: is the missing value actually missing or is it something else? We then read the policies on Kiva about exchange coverage. For instance, a lender gives 25 in US dollars and it changes to 250 in another currency. But when the money is repaid at 250 in the other currency, it only exchanges to 20 US dollars. The CURRENCY_EXCHANGE_COVERAGE_RATE measures how much such loss will be covered by the field partners. Some would cover 10% or 20%. So, it is more likely that the missing values indicating the loan does not have any coverage. So, it's more likely means 0.
Replacing the missing value with 0.

To analyze the CURRENCY_EXCHANGE_COVERAGE_RATE', the missing values and unique values are found out from the dataset. The CURRENCY_EXCHANGE_COVERAGE_RATE variable measures how much loss will be covered by the field partners during the currency conversion. Some conversion would result in percentages such as 10% or 20%. So, it is indicated that the missing values indicating the loan does not have any coverage. So, it's more likely means 0. The missing values are replaced with 0 so that the currency conversion rates which will be having least effect on the dataset.

Preparing training and test datasets.

  • X_test - This is the remainder of the data's independent variables that will not be included in the training phase but will be used to make predictions to assess the model's accuracy.
  • X_train - This is the training dataset
  • y_test - This data has category labels for your test data, these labels will be used to test the accuracy between actual and predicted categories.
  • y_train - this is the dependent variable which needs to be predicted by this model, this includes category labels against your independent variables, we need to specify our dependent variable while training/fitting the model.

Findings :¶

  • Comparing the histograms of 'LOAN_AMOUNT' and 'LOAN_AMOUNT_LOG', the skewed distribution of 'LOAN_AMOUNT' has been smoothed out.
  • Agriculture sector has the highest loan amount in total comparatively.
  • Entertainment and Wholesale sectors are having the lowest loan amounts.
  • Phillippines country has the highest number of loans comparatively.
  • Around the year 2018, the total number of loans are high and then decreased eventually.
  • There is a strong relationship between the two variables 'Days' and 'LOAN_AMOUNT'.h
  • There is no relationship between the two variables 'LOAN_AMOUNT' and 'LENDER_TERM'.
  • The accuracy score is more for logistic regression model.
  • Hence, model1 that is Logistic regression model is better for predicting the target variable "STATUS".

Managerial implications:¶

  • Crowdfunding is definitely very helpful for new entrepreneurs who have different ideas but are unable to invest in them.
  • It gives a hope for under developed nations for a successful economic growth.
  • Particularly for start up projects, Kiva crowdfunding encourages by providing the loans based on their motive to use the loan.
  • Since, this concept is based on funding from different people around the world, other organisations would also take a step forward to start such foundations in order to help the people who really have a good purpose.

Conclusions :¶

  • While it is extremely hard for small and medium businesses particularly start-ups to obtain financing, Crowdfunding which is also called as funding by different people around the world offers a feasible solution to seek investment from the angel investors. There will also be few cons connected with crowdfunding such as failure of the projects, fraud actions such as seeking the loan but not using for the stated purposes, exchange rates changing etc. Hence, in order to get the loan process to be done successfully depends on whether the borrower is genuine in their purpose, repaying their loans on time as per the agreement made with the lenders.

  • This project of Kiva crowdfunding demonstrates how complicated this process may be from operations perspective.Entrepreneurs, marketers, crowdfunding platforms, and their partners are all involved in the process of a project. This project summarizes new insights, as well as discover the characteristics that contribute to crowdfunding success in the contexts of entrepreneurship and charity.

  • We utilised pandas,numpy,regression models to determine the effecient results from the provided dataset. After series of operations and multiple methods for convenient data filtering we obtained the final required results.

  • We performed evaluation,cleaning and summarizing of data which are the three important stages in data analysis. We initially performed the first important step,data collection and analysis by reading the obtained data from our datasource which in our case is kiva.org.
  • We then performed cleaning operation with our data by performing series of operations like dropping and dealing with missing values and unwanted data.After which we stepped into the crucial part, analyzing the obtained data by finding the hidden patterns and relationships of the records present through which we find the insights and predictions.
  • In the final step we interpreted the results by performing number of classification method findings for the data present with us and concluded the operations by satisfactory results We have found that the best model as Logistic Regression for predicting the target variable 'STATUS'.
